        <TextBlock HorizontalAlignment="Left" Margin="233,101,0,0" TextWrapping="Wrap" VerticalAlignment="Top" Height="305" Width="471" FontSize="10" Grid.RowSpan="2"><Run Text="In the original 1978 Superman movie, Lois Lane names Superman after he has flown away from "/><LineBreak/><Run Text="his interview with her using the following line of dialogue..."/><LineBreak/><Run/><LineBreak/><Run Text="“What a super man. Hm. ‘Superman!&quot;"/><LineBreak/><Run/><LineBreak/><Run Text="2013's Man of Steel has Lois name Superman a little better. On paper, the dialogue is still pretty unsubtle "/><LineBreak/><Run Text="and ham-handed but the line is lifted by Amy Adams' delivery. She says the line with a hesitancy and a "/><LineBreak/><Run Text="little smile which shows that Lois knows this is kind of silly."/><LineBreak/><Run/><LineBreak/><Run Text="“How about... Sup-“"/><LineBreak/><Run/><LineBreak/><Run Text="(At this point, she is interrupted.)"/><LineBreak/><Run/><LineBreak/><Run Text="In &quot;Superman: The Animated Series&quot;, the cartoon Lois Lane also names Superman, except in this case it"/><LineBreak/><Run Text="is in a meeting with her editor after Superman's first public appearance."/><LineBreak/><Run/><LineBreak/><Run Text="“He's strong. He flies. He the Nietzschean fantasy ideal all wrapped up in a red cape. The superman.”"/><LineBreak/><Run/><LineBreak/><Run Text="Delivery of the lines aside, how is it that a cartoon manages to produce a more intelligent, less forced,"/><LineBreak/><Run Text="better written, more believable and far superior origin for Superman's name than either of two Hollywood"/><LineBreak/><Run Text="blockbusters?"/><LineBreak/><Run/><LineBreak/><Run Text="&quot;What a super man,&quot; indeed!"/></TextBlock>

